#: spack.spec.Spec.splice:7
msgid "Returns: a concrete, spliced version of the current :class:`Spec`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/spec.py:docstring of
#: spack.spec.Spec.splice:9
msgid ""
"When transitive is :data:`True`, use the dependencies from ``other`` to "
"reconcile conflicting dependencies. When transitive is :data:`False`, use "
"dependencies from self."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/spec.py:docstring of
#: spack.spec.Spec.splice:12
msgid "For example, suppose we have the following dependency graph:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/spec.py:docstring of
#: spack.spec.Spec.splice:14
msgid ""
"T\n"
"| \\\n"
"Z<-H"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/spec.py:docstring of
#: spack.spec.Spec.splice:20
msgid ""
"Spec ``T`` depends on ``H`` and ``Z``, and ``H`` also depends on ``Z``. Now "
"we want to use a different ``H``, called ``H'``. This function can be used "
"to splice in ``H'`` to create a new spec, called ``T*``. If ``H'`` was built "
"with ``Z'``, then ``transitive=True`` will ensure ``H'`` and ``T*`` both "
"depend on ``Z'``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/spec.py:docstring of
#: spack.spec.Spec.splice:25
msgid ""
"T*\n"
"| \\\n"
"Z'<-H'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/spec.py:docstring of
#: spack.spec.Spec.splice:31
msgid ""
"If ``transitive=False``, then ``H'`` and ``T*`` will both depend on the "
"original ``Z``, resulting in a new ``H'*``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/spec.py:docstring of
#: spack.spec.Spec.splice:34
msgid ""
"T*\n"
"| \\\n"
"Z<-H'*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/spec.py:docstring of
#: spack.spec.Spec.splice:40
msgid ""
"Provenance of the build is tracked through the :attr:`build_spec` property "
"of the spliced spec and any correspondingly modified dependency specs. The "
"build specs are set to that of the original spec, so the original spec's "
"provenance is preserved unchanged."
msgstr ""

